  "text": "Service account token auto-mounting in Kubernetes is controlled through three primary mechanisms:\n\n1. **Type Definitions** (staging/src/k8s.io/api/core/v1/types.go):\n   - PodSpec.AutomountServiceAccountToken: A boolean field (optional) that indicates whether the pod should have a service account token mounted (lines 3869-3871)\n   - ServiceAccount.AutomountServiceAccountToken: A boolean field (optional) on the service account that sets the default behavior for all pods using that account (lines 5852-5855)\n\n2. **Admission Controller** (plugin/pkg/admission/serviceaccount/admission.go):\n   - The ServiceAccount admission plugin (Plugin struct) handles the mutation and validation of pods during creation\n   - The Admit() method (lines 138-175) is the main entry point that processes pod creation\n   - The shouldAutomount() function (lines 254-265) implements the decision logic: pod setting wins, then service account setting, then default to true\n   - The mountServiceAccountToken() function (lines 416-482) adds the projected volume source containing the token secret\n   - TokenVolumeSource() (lines 485-524) generates the projected volume with the service account token, CA certificate, and namespace information\n   - Constants defined: DefaultAPITokenMountPath = \"/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount\" and ServiceAccountVolumeName = \"kube-api-access\"\n\n3. **Tokens Controller** (pkg/controller/serviceaccount/tokens_controller.go):\n   - The TokensController manages ServiceAccountToken secrets for ServiceAccount objects\n   - NewTokensController() (lines 72-130) initializes the controller with event handlers for both service accounts and secrets\n   - The syncSecret() method (lines 261-318) handles secret events and ensures tokens are populated with the actual token data\n   - The generateTokenIfNeeded() function (lines 368-436) populates the token secret with:\n     - The CA certificate (from rootCA parameter)\n     - The namespace name\n     - The JWT token (generated using the TokenGenerator)\n   - The TokensControllerOptions struct includes the TokenGenerator for creating JWT tokens\n\n4. **Service Account Controller** (pkg/controller/serviceaccount/serviceaccounts_controller.go):\n   - Creates and ensures the existence of default service accounts in every namespace\n   - NewServiceAccountsController() (lines 64-90) sets up watchers for both namespaces and service accounts\n   - Ensures service accounts with the default AutomountServiceAccountToken setting exist\n\n5. **Supporting Components**:\n   - pkg/serviceaccount/legacy.go: Handles legacy service account token claims\n   - pkg/serviceaccount/jwt.go: JWT token generation and validation\n   - pkg/serviceaccount/claims.go: JWT claims for service account tokens\n   - pkg/controller/serviceaccount/legacy_serviceaccount_token_cleaner.go: Cleans up legacy tokens after a grace period\n   - pkg/registry/core/serviceaccount/strategy.go: Validation and preparation strategies for service accounts\n   - pkg/registry/core/serviceaccount/storage/token.go: TokenRequest API for bound tokens\n   - pkg/apis/core/validation/validation.go: Pod and service account validation rules\n\n**Flow Summary**:\n1. When a pod is created, the admission controller checks if the token should be mounted\n2. If yes (based on the shouldAutomount logic), it injects a projected volume containing the token\n3. The tokens controller watches for these mounts and creates/updates the corresponding secret\n4. The secret is populated with the actual JWT token, CA cert, and namespace information\n5. The pod can then access the token at /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token"
